---
import Base from '../../../layouts/Base.astro';
import RelatedDestinations from '../../../components/RelatedDestinations.astro';
import { SITE, t } from '../../../data/i18n.js';
const lang = 'en';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const ui = t(lang);
const dest = ui.destinations.escorial;
const jsonLd = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org","@type": "TouristAttraction",
  "name": "Royal Monastery of San Lorenzo de El Escorial",
  "alternateName": ["El Escorial","The Escorial","L'Escorial"],
  "sameAs": ["https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q160836","https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/El_Escorial"],
  "isPartOf": {"@type": "UNESCOWorldHeritageSite","name": "Monastery and Site of the Escurial, Madrid"},
  "about": [
    {"@type": "Person","name": "Philip II of Spain","sameAs": "https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q527"},
    {"@type": "Thing","name": "Counter-Reformation"},
    {"@type": "ArchitecturalStyle","name": "Herrerian style"}
  ]
};
---
<Base lang={lang} title="Royal Monastery of El Escorial — Dramatized tour with official Heritage guide" description="Discover the Royal Monastery of El Escorial with María Victoria Solaz. Certified Heritage guide specialised in Philip II. Dramatized tours in 5 languages." jsonLd={jsonLd} path="/el-escorial/">
  <div class="w-full h-64 md:h-96 overflow-hidden">
    <img src={`${base}img/escorial/fachada.webp`} alt="Main façade of the Royal Monastery of El Escorial" class="w-full h-full object-cover" width="540" height="312" loading="eager" />
  </div>
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-4">{dest.name}</h1>
    <p class="text-xl text-sepia mb-8">Much more than a monastery. A palace, a library, a pantheon and the manifesto of a king who wanted to govern the world from a cell.</p>
    <section class="prose prose-lg max-w-none mb-12">
      <h2>Philip II didn't build a building. He built an obsession.</h2>
      <p>Guidebooks will tell you El Escorial was built to commemorate the Battle of Saint-Quentin. That's true, but it's only the surface. Philip II designed this place as the nerve centre of an empire stretching from Naples to the Philippines. Every stone, every corridor, every architectural decision carries a political and spiritual intention that only makes sense when someone explains it looking you in the eye.</p>
      <p>Here the most powerful king of his era governed from an austere room with a direct view of the Basilica's altar. Here Titian sent his last masterpieces from Venice. Here Sofonisba Anguissola painted portraits of the royal family. And here, in the Royal Pantheon, the kings of Spain rest in a silence that imposes more than any speech.</p>

      <h2>What Wikipedia won't tell you</h2>
      <p>El Escorial's hidden history lies in the details that only decades of studying Philip II can reveal. The psychology of a king who controlled an empire from his desk but couldn't control the gout that consumed him. The personal letters revealing a worried father, not just a monarch. The sedan chair in which he was carried at the end of his life — an object that says more about power and human fragility than any textbook.</p>

      <h2>UNESCO World Heritage since 1984</h2>
      <div class="my-8">
        <img src={`${base}img/guia/guia-disfraz-epoca.webp`} alt="María Victoria Solaz - visita teatralizada" class="rounded-lg w-full" width="1080" height="1440" loading="lazy" />
      </div>
      <p>UNESCO recognised El Escorial for its exceptional value as a Renaissance architectural complex. The Herrerian style, created by Juan de Herrera, influenced architecture across the entire empire — including the Palazzo Reale in Naples. Understanding El Escorial means understanding the aesthetic ambition of an entire era.</p>

            <div class="my-8">
        <img src={`${base}img/guia/guias-pasillo-monasterio.webp`} alt="Pasillos del Monasterio de El Escorial" class="rounded-lg w-full" width="1024" height="768" loading="lazy" />
      </div>

      <h2>The Imperial Axis: Escorial, Ávila, Segovia & Cuelgamuros</h2>
      <p>El Escorial doesn't exist in a vacuum. It forms a historical triangle with <a href="/en/avila/" class="underline">Ávila</a> and <a href="/en/segovia/" class="underline">Segovia</a> — three UNESCO World Heritage cities united by the history of Castile and Philip II's reign. And just kilometres away, <a href="/en/cuelgamuros/" class="underline">Cuelgamuros</a> (Valley of the Fallen) adds a layer of 20th-century history that completes the journey.</p>
    </section>
    <RelatedDestinations lang={lang} links={[
      { href: "/en/avila/", title: "Ávila — The mystic fortress", description: "If El Escorial is Philip II's brain, Ávila is his conscience. Saint Teresa, the walls and Castile's most austere beauty." },
      { href: "/en/segovia/", title: "Segovia — Aqueduct to Alcázar", description: "Juan de Herrera designed Segovia's Royal Mint for the same king. The imperial connection is direct." },
      { href: "/en/cuelgamuros/", title: "Cuelgamuros — Memory and stone", description: "10 km from El Escorial. Two monuments separated by four centuries, united by the same mountains." },
    ]} />
    <div class="cta-box rounded-lg p-8 text-center">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">{dest.productName}</h2>
      <p class="text-sepia mb-4">Book your tour with María Victoria</p>
      <a href={`${base}${lang}/el-escorial/${dest.productSlug}/`} class="inline-block btn-whatsapp px-8 py-3 rounded-lg font-medium">Details & booking →</a>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>
